<!-- ROSEMARY'S STORY -->
<section style="padding:clamp(4rem,8vw,7rem) var(--gutter);">
  <div style="max-width:var(--container); margin:0 auto;">
    <div class="about-grid">
      <div class="about-img-wrap">
        <img
          src="/images/rosemary-bietendorf.webp"
          alt="Rosemary Bietendorf, owner of The Gym of Tucson"
          width="600"
          height="800"
          loading="lazy"
          class="about-img">
      </div>
      <div class="about-grid__copy">
        <span class="about-ghost-number" aria-hidden="true">16</span>
        <div class="about-story__label">ROSEMARY BIETENDORF</div>
        <h2 class="about-story__heading">Owner, trainer, coach.</h2>

        <div class="about-story__body">
          <p>I didn't set out to open a gym. I set out to help people get stronger.</p>

          <p>It started in 2008 as a circuit coach at a women's-only gym in Tucson, learning from a mentor who saw something in me before I fully saw it in myself. She pushed me to get my personal training certification. I did. And from that moment, I couldn't stop.</p>

          <p>I trained people at the YMCA. In parks. In their living rooms. Wherever I could show up, I did. One of my boot camp classes became something more than a class. It became a crew. We started training for Spartan Races together, spending weekends in the dirt doing things none of us thought we could do. We finished all three, including the Beast, a half marathon with obstacles. The race ended. The boot camps didn't. Nobody wanted to stop.</p>

          <p>I spent years working for gyms that weren't mine, learning what I loved and what I knew I'd do differently. In 2015, I finally got to work for a locally owned gym, the kind I'd always wanted to be part of. The owners were good people who understood my ambition. In 2019, they helped me walk out the door to open The Gym of Tucson.</p>

          <p>We built something real from day one. A team of coaches who genuinely believed in the mission: creating a space that was safe, supportive, and non-judgmental, but still pushed people to find out what they were capable of.</p>

          <p>Then COVID hit. Two weeks before our one-year anniversary.</p>

          <p>We shut down. We pivoted. We used that time to move into the space we're in now, with an outdoor training area, big garage doors, and enough room to finally bring the park boot camp energy indoors. We survived because our community showed up for us the same way we'd shown up for them. I will never take that for granted.</p>

          <p>Giving back has always been part of who we are. Every year we host charity events that bring our members together around causes bigger than fitness. It is one of my favorite things we do.</p>

          <p>Sixteen years in, this is still the thing that gets me out of bed every morning: watching people surprise themselves. Watching someone lift more than they thought possible. Watching a nervous first-timer walk in and leave feeling like they belong somewhere.</p>

          <p>That was always the goal. Not the biggest gym. Not the flashiest. Just the one where people actually feel seen and leave stronger than when they walked in.</p>

          <p>We built that. Together.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-story__certs">
          <span class="badge">ACE Certified Personal Trainer</span>
          <span class="badge">ACE Sports Nutrition</span>
          <span class="badge">PPSC Certified</span>
          <span class="badge">RYT 200</span>
          <span class="badge">Powerlifting Coach</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

